<span id="fn_4016"></span>[525:4017](0070477.htm#fr_4016.md) <span
id="xi-p33.2"></span>

<span id="xi-p34"></span> Canon vii.  

<span id="fn_4017"></span>[525:4018](0070477.htm#fr_4017.md) <span
id="xi-p34.1"></span>

<span id="xi-p35"></span> <span id="xi-p35.1"></span>No one. This
re-affirms the action of Nicæa itself, and forbids the imposition of
anything novel as a creed by any authority whatever. Nothing, therefore,
which has not been set forth by Nicene authority (or by the
supplementing and co-equal councils of the whole Church, from the same
primitive sources) can be a creed, strictly speaking. It may be an
orthodox confession, like the <span class="Foreign"><span
id="xi-p35.2"></span>Quicunque Vult</span>, but cannot be imposed in
terms of communion, any more than the <span class="Foreign"><span
id="xi-p35.3"></span>Te Deum</span>  

<span id="fn_4018"></span>[525:4019](0070477.htm#fr_4018.md) <span
id="xi-p35.5"></span>

<span id="xi-p36"></span> <span id="xi-p36.1"></span>Any other faith.
The composition and setting north of <span id="xi-p36.2"></span>another
faith, as terms of communion, by Pius IV., bishop of Rome, <span
class="sc"><span id="xi-p36.3"></span>a.d.</span> 1564, and its
acceptance, with additional dogmas, at the opening of the Vatican
Council (so-called), <span class="sc"><span
id="xi-p36.4"></span>a.d.</span> 1869, brought the whole Papal communion
under this anathema of Ephesus.  

